{{Infobox company | name = Catch a Rising Star | logo = | type = | industry = [[Comedy club]]s | fate = | predecessor = <!-- or: | predecessors = --> | successor = <!-- or: | successors = --> | founded = December 1972 | founder = [[Rick Newman]] | defunct = <!-- {{End date|YYYY|MM|DD}} --> | hq_location_city = [[New York City]], [[New York (state)|New York]] | hq_location_country = [[United States]] | area_served = <!-- or: | areas_served = --> | key_people = | products = | owner = Suzy Yengo Esq. | num_employees = | num_employees_year = <!-- Year of num_employees data (if known) --> | parent = | website = {{URL|http://catcharisingstar.com}} }}
'''Catch a Rising Star''' is a chain of [[comedy clubs]], founded in [[New York City]] in December 1972 and owned by [[Rick Newman]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://theinterrobang.com/rick-newman-magic-catch-rising-star/ |title=Rick Newman and the Magic of Catch A Rising Star |date=2014-11-30 |website=The Interrobang |access-date=2017-10-14}}</ref> It has since spread to other areas, such as [[Las Vegas, Nevada|Las Vegas]] and [[New Jersey]]. Currently owned by Suzy Yengo Esq.
The original club in New York City was notable for its role in starting the careers of many famous singers and [[comedian]]s,<ref>{{Cite book |title=Comedy at the Edge: How Stand-up in the 1970s Changed America |last=Zoglin |first=Richard |publisher=Bloomsbury Publishing |year=2009 |isbn=9781582346250 |pages=95-96}}</ref> many of whom enjoyed later success in [[television]], [[theater]] and [[film]]. Among these are: [[Pat Benatar]]<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.vulture.com/2016/02/one-comedians-memories-of-la-and-ny-rooms.html |title=One Comedian Remembers the Many Rooms He Played in New York and Los Angeles |last=Federman |first=Wayne |date=2016-02-20 |website=[[Vulture.com]] |access-date=2017-10-14}}</ref>, [[Billy Crystal]]<ref name="bigcity">{{Cite web |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2012/12/02/arts/new-york-comedy-clubs-caught-in-a-turf-war.html |title=A Big City Is a Crowded Room |last=Zinoman |first=Jason |date=2012-11-28 |website=[[The New York Times]] |access-date=2017-10-14}}</ref>, [[Robin Williams]]<ref name="huffpo">{{Cite web |url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/jeryl-brunner/how-david-brenner-helped-_b_4986973.html |title=How David Brenner Helped Launch the Success of the Legendary Club Catch a Rising Star |last=Brunner |first=Jeryl |date=2014-03-20 |website=[[Huffington Post]] |access-date=2017-10-14}}</ref>, [[Bill Maher]]<ref name="huffpo"/>, [[Joy Behar]]<ref name="huffpo"/>, [[Jerry Seinfeld]]<ref name="huffpo"/>, [[Andy Kaufman]],<ref name="bigcity"/> [[Richard Belzer]],<ref name="huffpo"/> [[Adam Sandler]]<ref name="huffpo"/>, [[Elayne Boosler]]<ref name="huffpo"/>, [[Eddie Murphy]]<ref name="huffpo"/>, [[Larry David]]<ref name="huffpo"/>, [[Ray Romano]]<ref name="huffpo"/>, [[Richard Lewis (comedian)|Richard Lewis]]<ref name="huffpo"/>, [[Chris Rock]]<ref name="huffpo"/>, and [[Louis C.K.]]<ref name="ew"/>.
The original club has since gone out of business.<ref name="ew">{{Cite web |url=http://ew.com/books/2017/10/09/marc-maron-waiting-for-the-punch-excerpt/ |title=John Oliver, Danny McBride, and more talk failure with Marc Maron in Waiting for the Punch |date=2017-10-09 |website=[[Entertainment Weekly]] |access-date=2017-10-14}}</ref> Its former location, on 1st Avenue between East 78th Street and East 77th Street, is now occupied by Prince Properties, a [[real estate]] agency. In the late 1990s, the club was located on West 28th Street between 7th and 8th Avenues. The chain is currently negotiating to build a new club in the New York area.
Other locations throughout the US are located in [[Princeton, New Jersey|Princeton]], New Jersey, [[Reno]], Las Vegas, [[Twin River Casino]], Rhode Island and the new Catch A Rising Star on Broadway in New York.{{fact|date=November 2017}}
